Lebo Tshangela and Mayleen Vinvent The University of South Africa’s  Nanotechnology and Water Sustainability Research Unit is looking at technologies that will absorb heavy metals found in acid mine drainage polluted water. Much of the focus and publicity has been around the acid mine drainage crisis in the Witwatersrand, due to the areas historical gold mining activity. However, this problem affects the entire country as mining is critical to the economy. According to the South Africa Human Rights Commission (SAHRC), acid mine drainage has been reported in a number of areas, including the Witwatersrand gold fields, Mpumalanga and KwaZulu-Natal coal fields, and the O’Kiep copper district. The Western, Central and Eastern Basins are identified as priority areas requiring immediate action because of, among other things, the urgency of implementing intervention measures before problems become more critical and the proximity to densely populated areas. Acid mine drainage occurs when water comes into contact with exposed rock surfaces that are rich in sulphates, particularly iron sulphate also known as pyrite. The metals then dissolve out of the rock together with sulphates which results in the formation of sulphuric acid. The water that then contains both metals and sulphuric acid, and is therefore acidic. Water purification techniques Acid mine drainage has various effects on human health such as skin irritation, kidney damage, and neurological diseases amongst others. The Unit’s Dr Lueta de Kock says, “We are looking at technologies that will absorb or take up the metal that are in the acid mine drainage, so therefore to remove them from the aquatic environment and part of the work we do is also then once we have removed the metals from the water, we can then separate them out and recover them so that they become a resource rather than a waste or a by-product.” De Kock says the focus of her research is two-fold as she is looking at water purification techniques coupled with resource recovery. “So we looking at system that we can use to clean water.  Most of these focus on iron exchange or lignite exchange systems and the idea being not only that will we produce clean water but we can recover resources from the water. So one of the resources we can recover from acid mine drainage would be iron, that is a major component from the gold mine acid mine drainage, we can recover aluminium and we can then possibly use those recovered resources to cover some of the costs of treating the water.” De Kock adds that there are several projects running, two of which are at the point where small scale pilot studies may begin where a couple of a hundred litres per day will be treated on a continuous basis. How do we scale it up? Do that and we can end up trading thousands or hundreds of thousands of litres of water per day. Pilot project at Cradle of Humankind There is a large scale facility at the Cradle of Humankind which is piloting a process that uses high density sludge. Limestone, calcium carbonate are added to the acidic water which causes the pH to increase and this results in the metals precipitating out as sludge. De Kock says, “High density sludge means that we basically dewater that sludge so that it’s got a smaller volume, the water that is purified by that process then passes through a reverse osmosis membrane, after that it’s very pure. However, that process forms two waste products: the first is the sludge itself and the second is what we call the brine solution from the reverse osmosis process. And that is what is left after the clean water has passed through the membrane.” She adds, “We’re currently looking at what we can do with the sludge and with the brine to firstly recover more water from those products but also turn them into something that now is no longer a waste but it’s potentially a useful product.” But, De Kock warns that acid mine drainage is dangerous and poisonous to humans and the environment. Short-term treatment of acid mine drainage Federation for a Sustainable Environment CEO, Mariette Liefferink says between 2002 and 2012 acid mine water from the Pamodzi mine had been allowed to flow into the receiving environment without any intervention or mitigation. Liefferink says the Department of Water Affairs then decided to implement the short-term treatment of acid mine drainage that affected the central basin as a result of significant whistleblowing by advocacy groups. !function(e,t,s,i){var n="InfogramEmbeds",o=e.getElementsByTagName("script")[0],d=/^http:/.test(e.location)?"http:":"https:";if(/^\/{2}/.test(i)&&(i=d+i),window[n]&&window[n].initialized)window[n].process&&window[n].process();else if(!e.getElementById(s)){var r=e.createElement("script");r.async=1,r.id=s,r.src=i,o.parentNode.insertBefore(r,o)}}(document,0,"infogram-async","https://e.infogram.com/js/dist/embed-loader-min.js"); Diluting of Water not the solution Although efforts have been made by the Department of Water and Sanitaion, Liefferink says the short-term treatment for acid mine drainage is recognised by the department itself as an incomplete process. “That was why there was a launch by our former minister of water and sanitation Nomvula Mokonyane, for the long term treatment of acid mine drainage. However, it was supposed to be implement by 2014 to 2015 in order to address the high salinity in the Vaal river system because neutralized acid mine water still contains a significant salt or high salinity but it was delayed and may only now be implemented by 2022 or 2023. Which will impose risks on the water availability within the Vaal River system.” Corrosive impact of AMD on the environment !function(e,t,s,i){var n="InfogramEmbeds",o=e.getElementsByTagName("script")[0],d=/^http:/.test(e.location)?"http:":"https:";if(/^\/{2}/.test(i)&&(i=d+i),window[n]&&window[n].initialized)window[n].process&&window[n].process();else if(!e.getElementById(s)){var r=e.createElement("script");r.async=1,r.id=s,r.src=i,o.pa