r says, “DMR (Department of Mineral Resources) told us in a meeting in December 2017 that they were ready to start the rehabilitation process….but to date nothing has happened.” Despite huge misgivings about the accountability and negative environmental impact of mining, Liefferink explains that mining applications are being authorised in environmentally sensitive areas, “At the moment many mining applications being authorised in wetlands, within a sources of the river system, within pans in areas of fresh water ecosystems.” Department acknowledges threat of mining on water resources Department of Water and Sanitation Spokesperson, Sputnik Ratau says the department is looking into mine pollution. “In essence, the area of mine pollution is something that the department is looking at very strongly because we are aware that the impact on the environment and on the resource is such that it is not sustainable for us to continue without looking at the issue and correcting it.” Ratau says, “You must remember that this emanates from 150 years of mining that has been happening in the country and therefore it’s not something that is going to be resolved as quickly as possible. But in the same vein what we want say moving forward, included in the water use licences we will be issuing – we should be able to look at the fact that there must be the issue of insuring, that there is strong emphasis on corrective measures in terms of the water quality or the affluence that then gets discharged into the environment after or during the operation.” <a href="https://iono.fm/e/750416">Content hosted by iono.fm</a>